402
00:44:09,022 --> 00:44:10,357
See you, Kyu.

403
00:44:19,199 --> 00:44:20,533
Hi boss.

404
00:44:20,825 --> 00:44:22,952
Oh, Misuzu.

405
00:44:35,965 --> 00:44:39,427
This guy passed himself off
as Daisuke?

406
00:44:39,552 --> 00:44:41,054
That's right.

407
00:44:41,513 --> 00:44:45,392
We don't know his name,
so we call him "Mr. X."

408
00:44:46,017 --> 00:44:47,560
That's funny.

409
00:44:51,356 --> 00:44:56,069
Their faces and their heights
are probably different.

410
00:44:56,361 --> 00:44:58,238
Never seen him?

411
00:44:59,781 --> 00:45:01,908
When did you meet Daisuke?

412
00:45:02,951 --> 00:45:05,245
When I was in high school.

413
00:45:06,079 --> 00:45:09,290
We hooked up and broke up,
over and over.

414
00:45:10,959 --> 00:45:13,336
When did you last see him?

415
00:45:14,504 --> 00:45:16,089
When was it...

416
00:45:19,509 --> 00:45:25,265
His father had died, so he
went to the funeral... Around then.

417
00:45:26,933 --> 00:45:28,309
This is Daisuke.

418
00:45:30,019 --> 00:45:32,147
These are pretty old.

419
00:45:34,566 --> 00:45:36,985
At this time, were you...

420
00:45:37,527 --> 00:45:39,195
We were together.

421
00:45:40,447 --> 00:45:42,115
But around that time...

422
00:45:43,158 --> 00:45:44,951
The last time...

423
00:45:45,368 --> 00:45:50,582
He never talked about breaking up.
He was just suddenly gone.

424
00:45:51,166 --> 00:45:52,500
No calls or messages?

425
00:45:52,625 --> 00:45:55,503
Not at all.
I couldn't get through.

426
00:45:58,965 --> 00:46:02,302
But why did that guy
want Daisuke's past?

427
00:46:04,179 --> 00:46:07,140
His background was nothing special.

428
00:46:10,143 --> 00:46:11,144
An inheritance?

429
00:46:12,979 --> 00:46:14,230
I don't know.

430
00:46:16,441 --> 00:46:20,487
Maybe he got abducted by North Korea.

431
00:46:22,322 --> 00:46:28,077
I've heard about that. They steal
family registers and assume identities.

432
00:46:30,705 --> 00:46:35,210
Mr. X worked in forestry
in a small town in Miyazaki.

433
00:46:36,461 --> 00:46:41,674
Well, there are still plenty of
North Korean agents around, yeah?

434
00:46:41,966 --> 00:46:44,552
Not that conspiracy crap again.

435
00:46:46,179 --> 00:46:49,474
He thinks the Tohoku quake
was man-made.

436
00:46:49,557 --> 00:46:52,101
Wait a minute, that was...

437
00:46:52,185 --> 00:46:54,229
This is a real manhunt.

438
00:47:16,459 --> 00:47:22,006
Sorry for springing this on you.
Let me know if you...

439
00:47:31,432 --> 00:47:32,767
Sorry.

440
00:47:37,146 --> 00:47:38,398
Daisuke...

441
00:47:40,191 --> 00:47:41,693
What a dumbass.

442
00:47:44,654 --> 00:47:46,531
Such a dumbass.

443
00:47:51,077 --> 00:47:54,163
I thought I'd found him,
but this is...

444
00:47:57,417 --> 00:47:59,460
Sorry I blurted that out.

445
00:48:05,091 --> 00:48:06,092
Bye.

446
00:48:26,654 --> 00:48:32,410
<i>The DNA test confirmed that</i>
Mr. X wasn't Daisuke Taniguchi.

447
00:48:34,704 --> 00:48:36,539
I see...

448
00:48:37,832 --> 00:48:44,297
<i>That means you're</i>
neither married, nor a widow.

449
00:48:49,302 --> 00:48:50,428
<i>Rie?</i>

450
00:48:55,141 --> 00:48:56,476
<i>Are you alright?</i>

451
00:49:08,488 --> 00:49:12,659
I wonder,
whose life was I living with?

452
00:49:17,580 --> 00:49:21,167
"Whose life was I living with?"

453
00:49:25,546 --> 00:49:29,509
I didn't have the faintest idea
how to answer her.

454
00:49:32,345 --> 00:49:36,766
That X guy wanted to
hide his criminal past, no?

455
00:49:36,849 --> 00:49:39,686
A majorly nasty one at that.

456
00:49:41,521 --> 00:49:43,523
These sweets kick ass.

457
00:49:43,606 --> 00:49:44,774
I know.

458
00:49:49,445 --> 00:49:54,325
Nothing's riskier than
drawing the law's attention, no?

459
00:49:55,618 --> 00:49:58,371
That's a natural assumption.

460
00:49:59,497 --> 00:50:00,707
What's that?

461
00:50:01,499 --> 00:50:03,167
Brand fraud.

462
00:50:03,751 --> 00:50:08,756
Some shysters slap vintage stickers
on cheap-ass wines.

463
00:50:10,258 --> 00:50:14,721
Buyers don't want to look clueless,
so they keep quiet.

464
00:50:14,887 --> 00:50:16,556
That's ingenious.

465
00:50:24,731 --> 00:50:26,315
Interesting.

466
00:50:28,526 --> 00:50:33,823
Brand fraud reminds me,
I handled an impersonation case once.

467
00:50:33,906 --> 00:50:35,408
Impersonation?

468
00:50:35,908 --> 00:50:42,415
A 55-year-old man switched identities
with a 67-year-old and took his pension.

469
00:50:42,582 --> 00:50:45,543
Got a guilty charge and it went civil.

470
00:50:45,626 --> 00:50:49,505
The switch was pulled off by a broker.

471
00:50:53,801 --> 00:50:55,720
Wait, when was that?

472
00:50:56,387 --> 00:51:00,308
2000 and...what?

473
00:51:00,433 --> 00:51:04,395
<i>"Osaka pension fraud broker..."</i>

474
00:51:00,933 --> 00:51:02,935
Here it is. 2013.

475
00:51:03,352 --> 00:51:07,273
Around the time X came to Miyazaki.

476
00:51:08,316 --> 00:51:12,779
