01:29:50,094 --> 01:29:54,181
Soon after that,
he had an accident.

779
01:29:55,808 --> 01:29:56,850
An accident?

780
01:30:01,313 --> 01:30:04,900
<i>Fell from a building.</i>
A mall by the station.

781
01:30:06,318 --> 01:30:09,905
He said it was just a careless slip...

782
01:30:12,074 --> 01:30:13,867
...but off a building?

783
01:30:21,500 --> 01:30:22,876
How is your boss?

784
01:30:25,546 --> 01:30:27,631
It all came as a shock.

785
01:30:30,217 --> 01:30:35,848
He's over it now, but he was
depressed for a long time.

786
01:30:38,058 --> 01:30:40,227
He stepped out before, right?

787
01:30:42,104 --> 01:30:46,024
It's too hard for him.
Remembering.

788
01:30:52,990 --> 01:30:56,994
Hey... Can I ask you something?

789
01:30:57,327 --> 01:30:58,412
Sure.

790
01:31:04,668 --> 01:31:07,671
Was it suicide?
Makoto's death.

791
01:31:10,632 --> 01:31:14,219
As far as I'm aware,
that's unlikely.

792
01:31:17,806 --> 01:31:19,057
Good.

793
01:31:22,644 --> 01:31:25,189
He didn't stick with boxing,
did he?

794
01:31:27,149 --> 01:31:29,193
It seems he didn't.

795
01:31:34,990 --> 01:31:36,992
There's so much...

796
01:31:38,327 --> 01:31:40,913
...I want to talk to him about.

797
01:31:52,049 --> 01:31:54,843
<i>Foreigners, get out of Japan!</i>

798
01:31:56,053 --> 01:31:57,930
<i>Go to Hell!</i>

799
01:31:59,932 --> 01:32:03,936
<i>Racial and ethnic</i>
prejudice and discrimination.

800
01:32:05,103 --> 01:32:09,858
<i>Right now, fierce hatred</i>
is being spread through society.

801
01:32:09,358 --> 01:32:10,692
<i>"Hate speech"</i>

802
01:32:12,194 --> 01:32:13,695
<i>Filthy rats!</i>

803
01:32:13,779 --> 01:32:14,988
<i>Cockroaches!</i>

804
01:32:15,530 --> 01:32:18,200
<i>They don't deserve welfare!</i>

805
01:32:21,828 --> 01:32:23,830
Sota, keep it down.

806
01:32:23,914 --> 01:32:25,207
I'm home.

807
01:32:28,669 --> 01:32:33,340
<i>Why do we have to have</i>
our livelihoods threatened?

808
01:32:34,091 --> 01:32:36,510
<i>It's infuriating.</i>

809
01:32:52,526 --> 01:32:53,986
Knock it off!

810
01:32:55,946 --> 01:32:57,406
What's going on?

811
01:33:01,076 --> 01:33:02,286
What happened?

812
01:33:06,331 --> 01:33:07,416
Let's go.

813
01:33:43,785 --> 01:33:45,037
I'm sorry.

814
01:33:49,958 --> 01:33:52,294
You're not yourself lately.

815
01:33:54,463 --> 01:33:57,758
You're too caught up in your manhunt.

816
01:33:59,384 --> 01:34:03,805
I wish you wouldn't
bring that home with you.

817
01:34:10,896 --> 01:34:16,193
What does that man's life
have to do with yours?

818
01:34:20,364 --> 01:34:21,990
I don't know.

819
01:34:23,492 --> 01:34:29,164
It just...helps take my mind
off things, for some reason.

820
01:34:29,831 --> 01:34:32,167
Chasing another man's life.

821
01:34:34,044 --> 01:34:36,421
The son of an executed criminal?

822
01:34:37,881 --> 01:34:39,925
I don't understand you.

823
01:34:40,509 --> 01:34:42,511
I don't either.

824
01:34:44,513 --> 01:34:46,348
Running from reality?

825
01:34:48,558 --> 01:34:50,185
That's low.

826
01:34:50,352 --> 01:34:51,395
Is it?

827
01:34:52,229 --> 01:34:53,522
Am I to blame?

828
01:34:56,191 --> 01:34:58,193
You're running from me?

829
01:35:02,406 --> 01:35:04,074
Of course not.

830
01:35:11,081 --> 01:35:15,544
Just end it soon,
and go back to your old self.

831
01:36:31,161 --> 01:36:33,371
<i>Sorry to take your time.</i>

832
01:36:35,081 --> 01:36:36,458
Come on in.

833
01:36:37,292 --> 01:36:38,502
Good to see you.

834
01:36:42,088 --> 01:36:43,715
"Makoto Hara"?

835
01:36:46,801 --> 01:36:50,514
Cutting to the chase,
the man you married

836
01:36:51,139 --> 01:36:54,518
was a good man
who never committed a crime.

837
01:36:57,062 --> 01:37:00,482
Stealing somebody's identity
isn't a crime?

838
01:37:03,443 --> 01:37:05,403
He wanted our inheritance.

839
01:37:09,324 --> 01:37:12,661
Why switch with
an executed criminal's son?

840
01:37:16,957 --> 01:37:19,960
How is your brother any different?

841
01:37:24,214 --> 01:37:29,427
He was given the gift of life,
but he didn't want his.

842
01:37:30,470 --> 01:37:36,393
He was desperate to abandon
his identity and become a new man.

843
01:37:37,310 --> 01:37:39,688
Isn't that how Mr. Taniguchi felt?

844
01:37:41,523 --> 01:37:44,025
"Become a new man"?

845
01:37:45,068 --> 01:37:49,197
He never stopped being
an executed criminal's son.

846
01:37:59,708 --> 01:38:05,005
I'm sure Mr. Hara gave his all
for a second chance at life.

847
01:38:07,674 --> 01:38:12,220
Some people have to go to extremes
to start over.

848
01:38:23,440 --> 01:38:27,027
Daisuke might not be
alive anymore either.

849
01:38:48,173 --> 01:38:49,341
Hi.

850
01:38:50,759 --> 01:38:52,177
Hi.

851
01:38:58,725 --> 01:38:59,768
What's up?

852
01:39:13,156 --> 01:39:18,578
Now you're starting to think about
things that are beyond me.

853
01:39:38,598 --> 01:39:40,392
Our family name...

854
01:39:47,315 --> 01:39:50,485
We have to change it back
to Takemoto.

855
01:39:56,408 --> 01:39:57,659
I'm sorry.

856
01:40:00,662 --> 01:40:04,708
We can't be a burden on
the real Taniguchis.

857
01:40:16,177 --> 01:40:17,345
You know...

858
01:40:20,348 --> 01:40:25,395
I was sad when Dad died...

859
01:40:26,479 --> 01:40:28,148
...but not anymore.

860
01:40:35,780 --> 01:40:37,532
I just...

861
01:40:49,252 --> 01:40:50,754
I miss him.

862
01:40:54,257 --> 01:40:59,554
There's so much
I want to tell him, every day...

863
01:41:06,227 --> 01:41:07,520
I know.

864
01:41:16,780 --> 01:41:20,200
You really loved your dad,
didn't you?

865
01:41:37,759 --> 01:41:39,761
You really loved him.

866
01:41:55,568 --> 01:41:56,945
I'm sorry.

867
01:42:19,259 --> 01:42:21,386
<i>"Akira Kido"</i>

868
01:42:43,575 --> 01:42:47,787
<i>"Misuzu Goto" "Daisuke Taniguchi"</i>

869
01:42:58,047 --> 01:43:00,758
"This is a warning."

870
01:43:04,804 --> 01:43:10,810
"Delete this fake and
fraudulent account immediately."

871
01:43:17,150 --> 01:43:18,860
Sonezaki...

872
01:43:23,907 --> 01:43:27,619
Want zunda cakes?
Just got back from Sendai.

873
01:43:30,788 --> 01:43:31,748
Tea...

874
01:43:33,958 --> 01:43:36,586
I found the real Daisuke Taniguchi.

875
01:43:38,630 --> 01:43:43,468
So, Sonezaki sent a message
to the fake account?

876
01:43:44,594 --> 01:43:47,555
Omiura was telling me the truth.

877
01:43:47,639 --> 01:43:48,806
The truth?

878
01:43:48,932 --> 01:43:51,643
Makoto Hara changed names twice.

879
01:43:53,978 --> 01:43:58,983
First, he switched identities
with Yoshihiko Sonezaki.

880
01:43:59,108 --> 01:44:04,030
Later, he switched names again
with Daisuke Taniguchi.

881
01:44:05,281 --> 01:44:09,285
And this guy went to Miyazaki
as Daisuke Taniguchi?

882
01:44:10,036 --> 01:44:13,665
Rewriting his past,
till it became unreadable.

883
01:44:17,001 --> 01:44:20,755
So, where's this dude now?

884
01:44:26,219 --> 01:44:30,223
<i>Nagoya</i>

885
01:45:40,626 --> 01:45:41,919
Daisuke.

886
01:45:58,186 --> 01:45:59,812
You dumbass!

887
01:47:16,180 --> 01:47:18,224
<i>Thank you so much.</i>

888
01:47:18,349 --> 01:47:22,311
<i>"Investigation Report"</i>

889
01:47:27,191 --> 01:47:29,360
For Makoto Hara,

890
01:47:31,070 --> 01:47:33,990
three years and nine months with you

891
01:47:35,116 --> 01:47:37,743
surely meant everything to him.

892
01:47:40,246 --> 01:47:42,665
He wasn't with you long,

893
01:47:43,583 --> 01:47:46,127
but I'm sure he was truly happy.

894
01:47:49,422 --> 01:47:51,257
I hope so.

895
01:48:02,101 --> 01:48:06,105
It might be 20/20 hindsight, but...

896
01:48:12,111 --> 01:48:18,910
...I get the feeling now that maybe,
I never needed to know the truth.

897
01:48:23,414 --> 01:48:28,794
I mean, we met in this town,
fell in love...

898
01:48:31,339 --> 01:48:33,090
...became a family...

899
01:48:35,593 --> 01:48:37,136
...had Hana...

900
01:48:47,939 --> 01:48:50,816
Those truths are crystal clear.

901
01:49:20,972 --> 01:49:22,098
Read it?

902
01:49:23,224 --> 01:49:24,308
Yeah.

903
01:49:25,643 --> 01:49:26,852
You okay?

904
01:49:44,412 --> 01:49:49,875
Now I know...
why Dad was so kind, I think.

905
01:49:59,427 --> 01:50:00,511
Why?

906
01:50:03,014 --> 01:50:08,144
The things he wanted his father
to do for him, he did for me.

907
01:50:13,566 --> 01:50:15,234
I guess so.

908
01:50:23,492 --> 01:50:25,494
But that's not all.

909
01:50:28,289 --> 01:50:31,167
More than anything,
he loved you.

910
01:50:37,882 --> 01:50:39,884
Will you tell Hana?

911
01:50:50,686 --> 01:50:52,188
What do you think?

912
01:50:57,610 --> 01:50:59,320
I'll tell her.

913
01:51:02,239 --> 01:51:07,995
I'll tell Hana sometime,
about what kind of father he was.

914
01:52:21,652 --> 01:52:23,654
Rei isn't eating at all.

915
01:52:24,363 --> 01:52:29,326
No Dad. That one's Roa.
This one's Rei.

916
01:52:29,410 --> 01:52:32,621
Huh? Isn't that one Rei?

917
01:52:33,205 --> 01:52:35,207
This is the real Rei.

918
01:52:35,666 --> 01:52:38,169
Yeah? Are you sure?

919
01:52:38,544 --> 01:52:42,298
You're so forgetful,
you forgot!

920
01:52:42,381 --> 01:52:43,382
Did I?

921
01:52:43,549 --> 01:52:44,592
I'm home.

922
01:52:44,717 --> 01:52:46,343
Hi Mommy!

923
01:52:46,969 --> 01:52:48,095
Hi there.

924
01:52:48,387 --> 01:52:50,097
The party dragged on.

925
01:52:50,181 --> 01:52:51,557
Bath's still warm.

926
01:52:51,682 --> 01:52:52,725
Thanks.

927
01:52:53,350 --> 01:52:54,560
Been busy today?

928
01:52:55,394 --> 01:52:58,397
Daddy knocked over all of those.

929
01:52:58,522 --> 01:53:00,524
Daddy did? Oh no.

930
01:53:00,608 --> 01:53:03,569
Actually, I did it with that car.

931
01:53:04,028 --> 01:53:09,033
And they were so weak,
they all fell down.

932
01:53:10,117 --> 01:53:12,203
Okay, let's tidy up later.

933
01:53:13,579 --> 01:53:15,247
Get ready for bed.

934
01:53:19,168 --> 01:53:20,211
What's up?

935
01:53:22,546 --> 01:53:23,547
Nothing.

936
01:53:29,053 --> 01:53:31,180
My manhunt's over now.

937
01:53:33,224 --> 01:53:34,350
It is?

938
01:53:36,310 --> 01:53:37,645
That's great.

939
01:53:41,565 --> 01:53:45,152
Oh, I told Dad
we won't buy that house.

940
01:53:45,736 --> 01:53:49,156
We'll look if
it gets too cramped here.

941
01:54:05,381 --> 01:54:07,675
Hey, don't do that, it's cold!

942
01:54:07,758 --> 01:54:09,552
Try this. It's good.

943
01:54:09,760 --> 01:54:11,095
- It's good.
- It is.

944
01:54:11,178 --> 01:54:12,972
Mommy, that game.

945
01:54:13,264 --> 01:54:15,432
That game? Which one?

946
01:54:16,225 --> 01:54:17,309
Racer.

947
01:54:19,395 --> 01:54:23,065
You can play,
but only till your food comes.

948
01:54:24,066 --> 01:54:25,317
I lost.

949
01:54:26,235 --> 01:54:27,736
Restroom.

950
01:54:34,368 --> 01:54:35,786
A car! Yay!

951
01:54:38,289 --> 01:54:40,165
Daddy, the screen's weird.

952
01:54:42,126 --> 01:54:44,837
Oh, you must've touched something.

953
01:54:51,385 --> 01:54:56,390
<i>"Thanks for last night! I'm glad</i>
we met. You're unforgettable..."

954
01:55:01,645 --> 01:55:03,272
Mom's not back.

955
01:55:06,108 --> 01:55:09,320
Thank you for waiting.
One kids' meal.

956
01:55:09,653 --> 01:55:11,614
Oh, the food's here.

957
01:55:11,905 --> 01:55:16,368
Get me a spoon. A spoon
and a fork. Get them.

958
01:55:16,452 --> 01:55:18,454
Wow, it's quite fancy.

959
01:55:18,537 --> 01:55:19,705
It's not fancy.

960
01:55:19,830 --> 01:55:20,706
It is fancy!

961
01:55:35,220 --> 01:55:36,347
Enjoy.

962
01:55:40,726 --> 01:55:43,312
How old are the trees?

963
01:55:45,189 --> 01:55:49,193
They cut them down
after about 50 years.

964
01:55:52,529 --> 01:55:56,867
And once they become wood,
it lasts for another 50.

965
01:55:58,118 --> 01:56:02,122
50 years in the mountains,
50 years with humans.

966
01:56:03,791 --> 01:56:05,709
No kidding...

967
01:56:08,879 --> 01:56:13,550
So, you can't cut down
what you've planted.

968
01:56:14,385 --> 01:56:18,263
I guess...
I liked the sound of it.

969
01:56:18,472 --> 01:56:20,724
Of things being passed on.

970
01:56:22,393 --> 01:56:25,729
What fathers plant,
their sons cut down.

971
01:56:27,523 --> 01:56:29,817
Oh, you have children?

972
01:56:30,401 --> 01:56:31,402
I do.

973
01:56:31,652 --> 01:56:33,153
Grown up?

974
01:56:33,237 --> 01:56:36,699
One's 4,
and the other's 13.

975
01:56:37,658 --> 01:56:38,826
Two.

976
01:56:43,205 --> 01:56:45,749
You're from a different prefecture?

977
01:56:46,291 --> 01:56:47,376
Yeah.

978
01:56:49,420 --> 01:56:53,757
From Gunma originally.
You know, Ikaho Onsen?

979
01:56:53,924 --> 01:56:56,218
Oh yeah, it's famous.

980
01:56:56,343 --> 01:56:58,262
My family runs an inn.

981
01:57:00,514 --> 01:57:05,185
But my big brother took over,
so I left.

982
01:57:08,147 --> 01:57:13,861
I would've stayed.
I mean, hot spring baths every day?

983
01:57:16,029 --> 01:57:20,659
Well, my family and I
never got along anyway,

984
01:57:20,784 --> 01:57:24,163
and it brought me together
with my wife.

985
01:57:25,539 --> 01:57:27,916
Living your own way is best.

986
01:57:28,667 --> 01:57:31,670
It's nobody's life but your own.

987
01:57:33,005 --> 01:57:35,340
That's so true.

988
01:57:36,633 --> 01:57:41,263
I never want to let go
of the life I have now...

989
01:57:47,186 --> 01:57:48,520
I'd better go.

990
01:57:48,937 --> 01:57:50,773
Hey, check please.

991
01:57:51,565 --> 01:57:54,276
We talked so much,
for strangers.

992
01:57:54,401 --> 01:57:56,320
I really enjoyed it.

993
01:57:56,403 --> 01:57:57,488
Let's swap cards.

994
01:58:10,501 --> 01:58:11,668
I'm Suzuki.

995
01:58:12,711 --> 01:58:14,671
Sorry, I'm out of cards.

996
01:58:14,755 --> 01:58:15,839
No problem.

997
01:58:15,964 --> 01:58:17,299
I'm...

998
01:58:32,981 --> 01:58:37,986
Satoshi Tsumabuki

999
01:58:41,865 --> 01:58:46,870
Sakura Ando

1000
01:58:50,749 --> 01:58:55,796
Masataka Kubota

1001
01:59:07,975 --> 01:59:10,978
Nana Seino

1002
01:59:11,979 --> 01:59:14,982
Hidekazu Mashima

1003
01:59:15,983 --> 01:59:18,986
Kazutoyo Koyabu

1004
01:59:44,011 --> 01:59:47,014
Taiga Nakano

1005
01:59:48,015 --> 01:59:51,018
Yoko Maki

1006
01:59:52,019 --> 01:59:55,022
Akira Emoto

1007
02:00:04,364 --> 02:00:08,368
Based on the novel
"A Man" by Keiichiro Hirano

1008
02:00:09,369 --> 02:00:12,372
Screenplay by Kosuke Mukai

1009
02:00:13,373 --> 02:00:17,419
Directed by Kei Ishikawa

1010
